%N A395395 Decimal expansion of the area of the largest rectangle that can be inscribed in the unit half-width lemniscate of Bernoulli.
%C A395395 The lemniscate of Bernoulli can be described by (x^2 + y^2)^2 = a^2*(x^2 - y^2) in Cartesian coordinates, or r^2 = a^2*cos(2*phi) in polar coordinates, where a is the half-width. Here we take a = 1.
%C A395395 The problem was proposed by the English mathematician Robert Tucker (1832-1905) in 1894, and was solved by the German mathematician Emil Lampe (1840-1918) in 1895.
%C A395395 The width and height of the rectangle are phi - 1 = 1/phi (A094214) and sqrt(sqrt(5) - 2) = phi^(-3/2), respectively. Its aspect ratio is sqrt(phi) (A139339), and the length of its diagonal is sqrt(1/phi) (A197762).
%C A395395 It is assumed that the entire area of the rectangle is included in the interior of the lemniscate. Otherwise, the largest inscribed rectangle has vertices that are equidistant from the center, its width and height are 2^(3/4)*cos(Pi/8) and 2^(3/4)*sin(Pi/8), respectively, and its area is 1.
%H A395395 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395395/a395395.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395395 R. Tucker, <a href="https://archive.org/details/mathematicalque00unkngoog/page/n266/mode/1up">Problem 3318</a>, Mathematical Questions with Their Solutions: From the "Educational Times", Vol. 60 (1894), p. 126; <a href="https://archive.org/details/mathematicalque66unkngoog/page/n29/mode/1up">Solution</a>, by E. Lampe, ibid., Vol. 63 (1895), pp. 29-30.
%H A395395 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Lemniscate.html">Lemniscate</a>.
%H A395395 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemniscate_of_Bernoulli">Lemniscate of Bernoulli</a>.
%H A395395 <a href="/index/Al#algebraic_04">Index entries for algebraic numbers, degree 4</a>.
%F A395395 Equals sqrt(5*sqrt(5)/2 - 11/2).
%F A395395 Equals phi^(-5/2), where phi is the golden ratio (A001622).
%F A395395 Equals sqrt(phi^5 - 11).
%F A395395 Minimal polynomial: x^4 + 11*x^2 - 1.
%e A395395 0.3002831060007776078866947099484263673306360738353502...
